    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen using the new `vim.lsp.inlay_hint.enable` and `vim.lsp.inlay_hint.is_enabled` I am getting some strange behavior that doesn't seem correct in terms of how buffer local and global state should work. The steps below document the problem\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean`, open a completely clean neovim\r\n2. `:lua =vim.lsp.inlay_hint.is_enabled()`, check the global inlay hints and see that they are disabled\r\n3. `:lua vim.lsp.inlay_hint.enable(true)`, set the global inlay hints to being enabled by default for buffers\r\n4. `:lua =vim.lsp.inlay_hint.is_enabled()`, check again and see that it returns true because they were just enabled\r\n5. `:lua =vim.lsp.inlay_hint.enable(false, { bufnr = 0 })`,  disable inlay hints for a buffer 0 being the easiest for reproducing\r\n6. `:lua =vim.lsp.inlay_hint.is_enabled({ bufnr = 0 })`, check to see the current state of the buffer's inlay hints and see _true_\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIf I run `vim.lsp.inlay_hint.enable` the changes should be reflected. When I go to disable the inlay hints in a specific buffer, they should become disabled regardless of the current global default\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.0-dev-3070+gcf9f002f3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty 0.33.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nFrom repo (nightly build downloaded from releases)",
